In [4]:
#Compute the FFT
figure(figsize=(10,5))
dt=1/20480
t=np.arange(0,1,dt)
n=len(t)
fhat=np.fft.fft(data,n) #Compute the FFT
PSD=fhat * np.conj(fhat)/n #Power spectrum (power per freq)
freq=(1/(dt*n)) * np.arange(n) #creating x axis frequencies
L=np.arange(1,np.floor(n/2),dtype='int')

#plt.sca(axs[0])
plt.plot(freq[L],PSD[L],color='c',LineWidth=2, label='Noisy')
plt.xlim(freq[L[0]],freq[L[-1]])
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Based on the PSD plot above, we can use a threshold (for example, 0.5) that if some values are below that threshold, we assign 0 and if it's not, we hold the the same.

In [5]:
#Use PSD to Filter out Noise
indices=PSD >0.5  #find all frequencies with large power
PSDclean= PSD * indices #zero out all others
fhat = indices * fhat #zero out small fourier coeffs. in Y
ffilt = np.fft.ifft(fhat) #inverse FFT for filtered time signal

Wavelet Based Denoising¶

Source : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HSG-gVALa84¶

In [12]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import pywt
from skimage.restoration import denoise_wavelet
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.pyplot import figure
In [13]:
data=pd.read_table("2003.11.24.18.37.32",header=None)
data=data.iloc[:,6]

x_denoise=denoise_wavelet(data,method='BayesShrink',mode='soft',wavelet_levels=3,wavelet='sym8',rescale_sigma='True')

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.plot(data,label='Noisy')
plt.plot(x_denoise,label='Denoised')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [14]:
#Computing the FFT of Wavelet Based Denoised Data
figure(figsize=(10,5))
dt=1/20480
t=np.arange(0,1,dt)
n=len(t)
fhat=np.fft.fft(x_denoise,n) #Compute the FFT of the denoised data
PSD=fhat * np.conj(fhat)/n #Power spectrum (power per freq)
freq=(1/(dt*n)) * np.arange(n) #creating x axis frequencies
L=np.arange(1,np.floor(n/2),dtype='int')

fhat_noisy=np.fft.fft(data,n) #Compute the FFT of the noisy data
PSD_noisy=fhat_noisy * np.conj(fhat_noisy)/n #Power spectrum (power per freq)



plt.plot(freq[L],PSD[L],color='c',LineWidth=2, label='Filtered')
plt.xlim(freq[L[0]],freq[L[-1]])
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Computing the FFT of Wavelet Based(method1) Denoised Data
figure(figsize=(10,5))
dt=1/20480
t=np.arange(0,1,dt)
n=len(t)
fhat=np.fft.fft(x_denoise,n) #Compute the FFT of the denoised data
PSD=fhat * np.conj(fhat)/n #Power spectrum (power per freq)
freq=(1/(dt*n)) * np.arange(n) #creating x axis frequencies
L=np.arange(1,np.floor(n/2),dtype='int')

fhat_noisy=np.fft.fft(data,n) #Compute the FFT of the noisy data
PSD_noisy=fhat_noisy * np.conj(fhat_noisy)/n #Power spectrum (power per freq)


#plt.sca(axs[0])
plt.plot(freq[L],PSD[L],color='c',LineWidth=1, label='Filtered')
plt.plot(freq[L],PSD_noisy[L],color='k',LineWidth=0.08, label='Noisy')
plt.xlim(freq[L[0]],freq[L[-1]])
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Wavelet Based Denoising 3 (Discrete Wavelet Transform)¶

Source: https://dsp.stackexchange.com/questions/15823/feature-extraction-reduction-using-dwt¶

In [37]:
(ca, cd) = pywt.dwt(data,'haar')

cat = pywt.threshold(ca, np.std(ca)/2, mode='soft')
cdt = pywt.threshold(cd, np.std(cd)/2, mode='soft') 
#here, if you decrease the value in the denominator, the data would become more denoised.
ts_rec = pywt.idwt(cat, cdt, 'haar')

plt.close('all')

figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.subplot(211)
# Original coefficients
plt.plot(ca, '--*b')
plt.plot(cd, '--*r')
# Thresholded coefficients
plt.plot(cat, '--*c')
plt.plot(cdt, '--*m')
plt.legend(['ca','cd','ca_thresh', 'cd_thresh'], loc=0)
plt.grid('on')

plt.subplot(212)
plt.plot(data)
#plt.hold('on')
plt.plot(ts_rec, 'r')
plt.legend(['original signal', 'reconstructed signal'])
plt.grid('on')
plt.show()
